            <form>
               <orth>clabaisteir</orth>
            </form>
            <def>large, clumsy person (male) rather than brawler as used by Dwelly.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AOHenley_GlasgowIandMrsRMacDonaldcoltas-idp109710384">
            <form>
               <orth>blataillein</orth>
            </form>
            <def>a very outsize unattractive [sic]. [NOTES: the following explanation and the next three words written in second hand.] Thàinig e ’s blatàillein de thè còmh’ ris. Also used to describe a crowd of people (prob. batallion), e.g. Thàinig blatàillein a steach.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AOHenley_GlasgowIandMrsRMacDonaldcoltas-idp109708368">
            <form>
               <orth>pleabain</orth>
            </form>
            <def>(used of a man) a skinny, miserable, useless looking character with no obvious personality.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AOHenley_GlasgowIandMrsRMacDonaldcoltas-idp472264">
            <form>
               <orth>crabhàidseach</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Seann chràbhaidseach – an old decrepit person (female). (Donald MacIntyre in Sporan Dhòmhnaill uses “cranàidseichean”.)</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AOHenley_GlasgowIandMrsRMacDonaldcoltas-idp474496">
            <form>
               <orth>sgraoid</orth>
            </form>
            <def>(used of a woman) e.g. seann sgraoid. Untidy older woman who takes no care of her appearance. Used also as a derogatory term describing an unpopular person, probably female.</def>
         </entry>
